<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Detroit_Tigers&action=edit&section=59.php.html" title="Edit section: Uniforms and logos">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Uniforms_and_logos">Uniforms and logos</span></h2>
<dl>
<dd><i>See also: <a href="Major_League_Baseball#MLB_uniforms" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball#MLB uniforms</a> (including image of baseball-cap logos of the 30 MLB franchises)</i></dd>
</dl>
<p>The Tigers have worn essentially the same home <a href="Baseball_uniform" title="Baseball uniform">uniform</a> since 1934 — solid white <a href="Jersey_(clothing)#In_sports" title="Jersey (clothing)">jersey</a> with navy <a href="Piping_(sewing)" title="Piping (sewing)">piping</a> down the front and an Old English "D" on the left chest, white pants, navy <a href="Baseball_cap" title="Baseball cap">hat</a> with a white letter D in the <a href="Blackletter" title="Blackletter">blackletter</a> or <i>textur</i>/<i>textualis</i> typeface associated with <a href="Middle_English" title="Middle English">Middle</a> and <a href="Early_Modern_English" title="Early Modern English">Early Modern</a> English and popularly referred to as "Old English" even though it was not used for <a href="Old_English" title="Old English">that language</a>. When the Tigers are the visiting team, the D on their hats is orange and the word "DETROIT" appears across the shirt. A version of the team's blackletter D was first seen on Tigers uniforms in 1904, after using a simple block D in 1903. The blackletter D appeared frequently after that until being established in 1934.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1960, the Tigers changed their uniform to read "Tigers", but the change only lasted one season before the traditional uniform was reinstated.</p>
<p>In 1995, the Tigers introduced an <a href="Third_jersey" title="Third jersey">alternate jersey</a>, solid navy with the team's alternate <a href="Logo" title="Logo">logo</a> (a tiger stepping through the "D") on the chest. It was worn a few times and then abandoned.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The Tigers are the only team in Major League Baseball to have a color on their <a href="Road_(sports)" title="Road (sports)">road</a> uniforms that is not on their home uniforms (orange). They are also the only MLB team that does not wear <a href="Batting_practice" title="Batting practice" class="mw-redirect">batting practice</a> jerseys during <a href="Spring_training" title="Spring training">spring training</a>, instead electing to wear their normal uniforms in lieu of the colored tops that most teams wear for batting practice.</p>
<p>The Tigers use slightly different versions of the initial logo on the cap and jersey.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span>[</span>52<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table>
<tr>
<td style="width:200px; text-align:center;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg" class="image"><img alt="Detroit Tigers logo.svg" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e3/Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg/100px-Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e3/Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg/150px-Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e3/Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg/200px-Detroit_Tigers_logo.svg.png 2x" /></a></td>
<td style="width:200px; text-align:center;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg" class="image"><img alt="Detroit Tigers Insignia.svg" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg/100px-Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg.png" width="100" height="100" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg/150px-Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg/200px-Detroit_Tigers_Insignia.svg.png 2x" /></a></td>
